<div1 type="letter">

<note type="curatorial">10</note>

<opener>

<address>
<addrLine>Thomas W. Wright</addrLine>
<addrLine>P.O. Box 738</addrLine>
<addrLine>Peabody College</addrLine>
<addrLine>Nashville 5, Tennessee</addrLine>
</address>
<dateline>Feb. 21, 1960</dateline>
<address>
<addrLine>Dr. Joh G. Neihardt</addrLine>
<addrLine>Department of English</addrLine>
<addrLine>University of Missouri</addrLine>
<addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
</address>
<salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt:</salute>
</opener>

<p>How I cherish the moments I have spent with you to discuss matters that are close to us; in a lifetime a man is blessed indeed if he finds a true friend to whom he can open his heart and mind. You have been such a friend to me. I have felt a companionship with you such as I feel when I read Henry David Thoreau's "Walden."</p>

<p>When I finish my year of work at Peabody in June for the master of arts degree in library science I hope to obtain a position with a college of university library.</p>

<pb/>

<p>I have become keenly interested in the history of the trans Missouri frontier and recently completed a term paper on the subject of "The Literary Culture of the Trans-Missouri Frontier in the 19th Century." Where ever I locate I hope to donate time to serious writing of Western Americana, and among my projects is a history of the former Fort Robinson so intimately associated with the tragic death of Crazy Horse and the Cheyennes under Dull Knife.</p>

<p>Dear Friend, if God wills we shall meet again soon to talk over plans and warm our spirits. Peace be with you and the joy and companionship of your children and grand children.</p>

<closer><salute>Affectionately,</salute>
<signed>Thomas W. Wright</signed>
</closer>
